{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":"2026-03-30T02:59:35.774Z","tool_name":"write_file","tool_id":"write_file_1774839575774_0","parameters":{"content":"# Resources Catalog: Mathematics Distillation Challenge\n\n## Summary\nThis document catalogs all papers, datasets, and computational tools gathered for the Mathematics Distillation Challenge (Equational Theories).\n\n## Papers\nTotal papers downloaded: 1\n\n| Title | Authors | Year | File | Key Results |\n|-------|---------|------|------|-------------|\n| The Equational Theories Project: Advancing Collaborative Mathematical Research at Scale | Bolan et al. | 2025 | papers/2512.07087_Equational_Theories_Project.pdf | Complete implication graph between 4694 laws |\n\nSee papers/README.md for detailed descriptions.\n\n## Prior Results Catalog\nKey theorems and properties available for the challenge:\n\n| Result | Source | Statement Summary | Used For |\n|--------|--------|-------------------|----------|\n| Duality Symmetry | ETP Paper (Section 2) | $E_1 \\models E_2 \\iff E_1^* \\models E_2^*$ | Reducing knowledge search space |\n| Constant Law $E46$ | ETP Paper | $x \\diamond y = z \\diamond w \\implies E$ for any $E$ except $E2$ | Handling constant cases |\n| Singleton Law $E2$ | ETP Paper | $x = y \\implies E$ for all $E$ | Universal implication |\n| Trivial Law $E1$ | ETP Paper | $E \\implies x = x$ for all $E$ | Universal target |\n| Undecidability | Birkhoff (1935) | Equational implication is undecidable in general | Managing expectations |\n\n## Computational Tools\n\n| Tool | Purpose | Location | Notes |\n|------|---------|----------|-------|\n| Lean 4 | Formal Proof Assistant | [leanprover/lean4](https://github.com/leanprover/lean4) | Ground truth for all implications |\n| Vampire / Prover9 | Automated Theorem Provers | (Standard ATP tools) | Finding proofs for unknown implications |\n| Mace4 | Finite Model Finder | (Standard tool) | Finding counterexamples |\n| Equation Explorer | Implication Navigation | [teorth.github.io](https://teorth.github.io/equational_theories/explorer/) | Visualizing the graph |\n| Graphiti | Hasse Diagram Visualization | [teorth.github.io](https://teorth.github.io/equational_theories/graphiti/) | Visualizing clusters |\n| teorth/equational_theories | Full Project Repository | code/equational_theories/ | Scripts, data, and Lean formalizations |\n\n## Datasets\n\n| Dataset | Source | Description |\n|---------|--------|-------------|\n| SAIR Foundation Challenge Data | Hugging Face | `normal`, `hard1`, `hard2`, `hard3` subsets for Stage 1 |\n| Implication Graph (Raw) | ETP Repository | Full list of 22M+ edges |\n| `equations.txt` | ETP Repository | List of 4,694 laws (E1 to E4694) |\n\n## Recommendations for Proof Construction\n\nBased on the gathered resources, the following strategy is recommended for the \"Mathematics Distillation\" task:\n\n1.  **Syntactic Analysis**: Focus on the presence of variables and the \"shape\" of the equation. Small magmas often refute implications that seem plausible but lack syntactic necessity.\n2.  **Structural Categorization**: Categorize laws into families (e.g., Absorptive, Constant, Commutative, Associative).\n3.  **Duality Utilization**: Ensure the model understands that a result for $A \\models B$ immediately gives a result for $A^* \\models B^*$.\n4.  **Local Context**: Use the `explain_implication.py` script from the ETP repository to generate \"chains\" of implications for the most common laws.\n","file_path":"resources.md"}}
